post_text:
Dorchester students competed in the Journalism Education Association Winter High School Journalism Competition. From across the state, 396 students from 28 schools competed in the Winter Journalism Competition. Most of the schools were from Omaha or Class A, and Dorchester was the smallest represented. The competitors received certificates for entries judged Superior, Excellent, and Honorable Mention. Only the best entries received awards. “It is one thing to share news within your school community, but quite another to be evaluated by a professional and deemed worthy of recognition,” said JEA state director Marsha Kalkowski.

Breanna Muff received an Excellent in News/Feature Photography. Danni McKnight received a Superior in Yearbook Sports Writing and an Excellent in Sports/Action Photography. Alli Novak received an Excellent in Yearbook Sports Writing. Jose Real received an Honorable Mention in Advertising. They are advised by Mrs. Sandy Severance. We are very proud of their accomplishments!

post_text:
July 22, 2020

Hello from Dorchester Public School!

To ease the financial burden on families caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, basic school supplies will be purchased by Dorchester Public School this year. Therefore, this year we will not have a typical school supply list. Please refer to our website at dorchesterschool.org and click on the 2020-21 Supply List for the few items that will still need to be provided by parents.

At this time we are not requiring masks, but recommending them. The district has purchased enough premium adjustable, reusable, washable masks for each student to have 2 each. We are scheduled to get more masks from the state, so do not feel like you need to purchase masks as we will provide them. Masks worn at school must follow the dress code, and should be two-layered. Just a reminder that handkerchiefs are not appropriate face coverings.

Again more information will come out the week of August 3rd regarding reopening plans!

Thank you!

Daryl Schrunk
Superintendent

post_text:
Reopening School in the Fall
Initial Plans
[June 2020]

At this time, Dorchester Public School is setting plans in place for reopening school in the fall. Our scheduled first day of school is Wednesday, August 19. Our 2020-2021 calendar can be found on our website (dorchesterschool.org).

Please know that the safety and well-being of our students and staff is always a priority. We will follow the directed health guidelines in place. Our plans will allow us to adjust according to any health concerns (“risk dial”) so we can continue educating our students. More details to come!
text:
Reopening School in the Fall
Initial Plans
[June 2020]

At this time, Dorchester Public School is setting plans in place for reopening school in the fall. Our scheduled first day of school is Wednesday, August 19. Our 2020-2021 calendar can be found on our website (dorchesterschool.org).

Please know that the safety and well-being of our students and staff is always a priority. We will follow the directed health guidelines in place. Our plans will allow us to adjust according to any health concerns (“risk dial”) so we can continue educating our students. More details to come!

post_text:
Attention Parents!

The requirement for students entering the7th grade to have a physical exam is Nebraska state education law and we do not have the ability to waive that requirement. However, the physicals that the current 7th graders have for the 2019-2020 school year can be used for NSAA purposes for the 2020-2021 school year.

After discussions with legal counsel and our insurance provider, due to our catastrophic insurance requirements, all current 8th grade students that are going to enter the 9th grade in 2020, will STILL be required to get a PPE for the 2020-2021 school year. All other high school students entering grades 10, 11 & 12 grades that have a the PPE paperwork for 2019-2020 school year, can use that physical for the 2020-2021 school year.

If you have any questions, please contact the school.
